dwc_identificationRemarks: Hybrid garden cultivar and not true N. pseudonarcissus with smaller flowers and outer tepals distinctly paler than trumpet.
Robert Kral identified this population based on a specimen collected by S. Baskauf #83.
This determination is believed to be incorrect.
Source population identified by botanists of the Tennessee Division of Natural Areas
Individuals part of a population identified and monitored by TN Department of Environment and Conservation.

Buds look like Q. coccinea.  Leaves are intermediate.  Acorns are also intermediate in that they are shaped like Q. palustris (cup and acorn) but appear a bit too large and also the cup appears to curve inward at its apex as it meets the nut.
ID based upon images and description at EOL.  Accepted name based upon ITIS
Vanderbilt Alumnus Magazine 2(5):131 (March 1917) states that the Garland Oak was an overcup oak.
Vanderbilt Register 10 (2):5 (Sep. 15, 1989) states that the tree was a bur oak.
The image http://bioimages.vanderbilt.edu/baskauf/12469 appears in Nesom (2010) on p. 27.
